Why Jerome Powell Must Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to what may be the most powerful position within the world economy?
An incorrect decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to regulate the banking system adequately, thereby laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting feeling of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a number of clichés as to why the current central bank chief, Jerome Powell, should be confirmed in office.
It would be a proof of non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience is needed, who will lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I have already heard 25 years ago, when I was chairman of the economic advisory board of US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was an issue.
They were sufficient to convince Clinton, and the country has paid dearly for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied Volcker a second term in office after he had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed Volcker a lot, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, a follower of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to conflicting goals are needed.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets are efficient, stable, fair, and competitive on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have always held clearly different but clearly articulated views on these issues (at least until the Republicans fell into populist madness).
From my perspective, the Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unbridled markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally only in tight labor markets have marginalized groups been brought into the economy and wage differences reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test for every US central bank chief.
Already now, the USA is facing difficult decisions on what to do about inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially problems stemming from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, who have still not regained their pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and thus an increase in unemployment) be a worse medicine than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the incorrect pricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even stronger and more pervasive mispricing of assets related to climate change.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man for the hour.
First, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby risked the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take any action regarding climate risk, even though other central bankers worldwide have already declared this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues are not part of the Fed's mandate, yet he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater danger to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
An evident lack of competition and insufficient regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce credit availability for small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell with the Fed's reaction to the pandemic.
Yet any second-year student would have known that during a recession one must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT has argued, Powell is not particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board, with regard to tightening monetary policy, has been marked during the past decade by a series of misjudgments, dating back to the "taper tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the concern of the central bank, it is a fact that the bank's policy has significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early increase in interest rates can choke growth, weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal involving stock trading by senior Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparently lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump having already weakened trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer who decides when certain market transactions would appear improper.
The Fed resembles the US Supreme Court in some respects.
It is supposed to be above politics, yet since Bush v. Gore at the latest, we know that is not the case.
Trump made that clear for everyone who still had doubts.
Also the Fed is supposedly independent, however Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is also not the case by following their party's deregulation agenda.
Yet while the central bank board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power traditionally concentrates much more in the hands of the central bank chief than in the hands of the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank chief who decides what comes up for a vote and which topics are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is only one example where it is extremely important who is sitting at the head of the table.
The US needs a central bank that truly commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competition-determining financial sector.
Anyone who believes that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far lacks insight.
We need neither an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-oriented lawyer like Powell.
What is needed is someone who has a deep understanding of economics and shares Biden's concerns about inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden does not have to look far to find someone who has already proven their abilities.
Lael Brainard is already a member of the central bank board, where she has demonstrated her competence and earned the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chair who maintains continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but who shares his economic and social program.
